    "recap_headline": "Wake Forest Athletics",
    "recap_text": "CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. \u2013\nThe No. 24 Wake Forest baseball team (17-7, 4-5 ACC) dropped the series finale, 14-4, to No. 9 Virginia (20-5, 6-3 ACC) on Sunday afternoon at Disharoon Park.\nJuniors\nKade Lewis\nand\nBlake Schaaf\nboth collected a pair of hits to pace the Demon Deacons, including a double from each.\nRight fielder\nLuke Costello\nbecame the first Deac to reach 30 RBIs this season, collecting his 30th and 31st on a two-RBI single in the third inning to open the scoring.\nFreshman\nJD Stein\nfinished 3-for-8 over the last two games of the series with a double, a homer, and four RBIs.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nStarting pitcher\nTroy Dressler\nopened things up with a 1-2-3 bottom of the first to keep the game knotted after an inning of play.\nWake Forest put a runner in scoring position with two away, but was unable to strike first in the top of the second.\nDressler ran his strikeout total to four through the first two innings, striking out the side in the second.\nThe Demon Deacons mounted a two-out rally, striking for three runs with two away to grab an early lead in the top of the third.\nAfter the first two batters of the inning were retired, junior\nJavar Williams\nworked a walk to get things going with two away.\nFirst baseman\nKade Lewis\ncollected the first hit of the contest, singling to center field to move Williams to third.\nLewis moved to second on a stolen base to put two in scoring position.\nThird baseman\nDalton Wentz\nfought off a pair of pitches to earn a walk and load the bases.\nSophomore\nLuke Costello\nambushed the first pitch he saw, sending a laser 105 mph off the bat into left field to plate a pair of runs.\nCatcher\nMatt Conte\nwent the other way on a 1-0 pitch, punching a single to right field to plate Wentz and make it 3-0 in favor of the Demon Deacons.\nVirginia answered with two runs in the bottom of the third.\nWake Forest punched back with a run in the top of the fourth, as\nJD Stein\ncontinued his outstanding weekend with an opposite-field double down the line in right to bring in\nBlake Schaaf\n.\nThe Cavaliers took the lead with five runs in the fourth.\nA 6-4-3 double play got the Deacs out of the fifth inning unscathed.\nVirginia added a pair of runs in the sixth to take a 9-4 lead.\nUVA added four runs in the seventh.\nVirginia took the series finale, 14-4, in eight innings.\nFROM COACH WALTER\n\"I needed to do a better job managing our bullpen in that game. We knew we wouldn't get a ton of length out of Troy [Dressler]. He's just building up. He hadn't thrown more than 55 pitches in an outing. Probably should have made a different pitch call there in the third, maybe would have gotten us out of that inning scoreless. Maybe we could have gotten him through the fourth. Once the third became taxing for him, I probably should have gone to [Evan] Jones to start the fourth. Jones came in and was just uncharacteristically not landing his slider. It's a good teaching moment for him. We'll use this to grow on and get better. We have a big week coming up, Elon at home, and then three games at home against Cal. I like the way we're starting to swing the bats. I like the way our lineup's coming together. We're getting some length in our lineup. I still like our pitching options. We've got a good ball club, and coming into a part of our schedule where we should be successful.\" - Head Coach\nTom Walter\nUP NEXT\nWake Forest returns home for the next four games, starting with a midweek matchup against in-state foe Elon on Tuesday, Mar. 24, with first pitch set for 6 p.m. from David F. Couch Ballpark.\nFOLLOW THE DEACS\nGoDeacs.com\n|\nTwitter\n|\nInstagram\n|\nFacebook",
